time required: 15 minutes
---

Wash and dry produce. Dice @sweet potato{1} into ½-inch pieces.

In a large #microwave-safe bowl{}, toss sweet potato with half the @garlic powder{2%teaspoon}, @salt{} and @pepper{} until coated.

Add @butter{2%tablespoon} to bowl and cover tightly with #plastic wrap{}; microwave until sweet potato is tender and steaming, ~{6-7%minutes}. Remove plastic wrap and stir.

While sweet potato cooks, remove and discard any large stems from @kale{4%ounce}; chop if desired. Place kale in a second large #bowl{}. Using your hands, massage kale with a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} (similar to how you would knead dough) until leaves are tender, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Don't skip the massaging step—massaging helps the kale leaves wilt slightly, lending a tender (never fibrous!) texture.

Pat @ranch steak{10%ounce} dry and thinly slice against the grain.

Drizzle @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a hot large #pan{}. Add steak and season with half the @dried thyme{1%teaspoon}, remaining garlic powder, salt, and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, to desired doneness, ~{3-6%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan and let cool slightly.

Heat pan used for steak over high heat; add sweet potato. Cook, stirring constantly, until sweet potato is browned, ~{30-60%seconds}. Turn off heat; transfer to bowl with kale.

Reserve 4 tsp @creamy balsamic dressing{3%ounce} in a small #serving bowl{}.

Add @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon} to bowl with sweet potato and kale. Drizzle with as much remaining dressing as you like; toss to combine.

Serve salad topped with steak, drizzled with reserved dressing, and sprinkled with @pecans{½%ounce} and @dried cranberries{1%ounce}.

> Steak is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.